題名: 英語全球化對台灣英語教育的發展與挑戰-英語為國際通用語對培養學生英語表達能力的挑戰
其他題名: Making Effective Elf Presentation for Academic Purposes
作者: 高實玫
貢獻者: 外國語文學系
日期: 2012
上傳時間: 2013-06-14 15:35:34  (UTC+8)
摘要: 英語是目前國際社會中使用最廣泛的溝通語(English as a Lingua Franca, ELF)，在高等教育環境中，英語也是最常被用來作為學術演示(academic presentation)、互動討論 (question & answer) 及一般溝通的語言，然而因為ELF使用者的文化背景、母語及英語學習歷程差異極大，如何使學術演示及後續的討論溝通精準且有效率，是對專業學門教師及學習者的一大挑戰。近年來ELF領域的研究學者提出：ELF使用者的溝通模式與英語為母語者(native speakers of English, NS)不同，這項假說已由歐洲ELF口語語料庫The VOICE Project中的語料分析得到有利證實。本計畫將進一步廣泛蒐集在台灣ELF環境下之高等教育各學術領域中學生在客堂中進行學術演示及演示後討論之語料，並進一步比較母語人士及專業學術領域中ELF使用者對於這些語料中之表達技巧及溝通效率的評定標準和其間的異同。本三年期計畫的第一年將做相關文獻的研讀，並借助The VOICE Project語料庫中的溝通特徵發展出一套ELF表達能力評估問捲，邀請高等教育體系中不同專業學門且具備ELF學術演示經驗的教師，及 NS教師分兩組對ELF表達能力評估表進行專家回饋，這兩組專家的意見會用來修正ELF表達能力評估表。第二年將蒐集不同領域之大學部或研究所學生在課堂中所做的學術演示及討論作為語料，並邀請在台灣就讀之英語流利的國際生和NS學生分兩組，依照第一年發展出來的ELF表達能力評估表對語料進行評選，除了對這兩組學生的評選結果作統計比較外，並針對被選為優秀及有效率的演示者之語料做分析，以便歸納出其語言及非語言表達技巧和特徵。第三年將針對所歸納出的表達技巧和特徵設計適用於各學術領域的教學流程和練習活動，並實際在課室中實施並檢驗其成效。 本計畫最終的目標是由ELF使用者角度發展出一套教學流程及配套活動，以協助高等教育各學術領域的教師協助他們的學生發展出有溝通效率的學術演示及表達方法，並能成功的掌控後續的討論時間，使學生在各領域的ELF場域中達到有效率的表達。English as a Lingua Franca (ELF) is generally a ‘contact language’ between people who share neither a common native tongue nor a common culture, and for whom English is the chosen language of communication. Due to the tremendous varieties in ELF users' linguistic, cultural, and professional backgrounds, the discourse features of such communication vary greatly. The assumption that ELF communication is different from the interaction among native speakers has been verified from several studies based on the Vienna-Oxford International Corpus of English, (hence, the VOICE Project). This spoken ELF corpus collected from users of English across European countries. These studies investigate the phonological, lexical-grammatical, and pragmatic aspects of ELF interaction. The VOICE Project made an important step toward the claim that ELF is “a legitimate, and not a deviant, linguistic code of intercultural communication” (Hulmbauer, Bšhringer, & Seidlhofer, 2008, p.30). As global connectivity becomes a buzzword in higher education, making comprehensible and intelligible presentation to ELF audience plays an important part in ones' academic development. Current ELF research has focused on describing the discourse features of casual ELF communication. The proposed three-year project aims to extend the investigation into academic presentation from the aspects of ELF audience and define what efficient academic presentation means to EFL community. Academic presentation usually includes two parts: the presentation and the question & answer sessions. The former session requires one's production skills, while the latter session demands one's interaction skills with the audience. The current project plans to first develop an evaluation rubrics of effective ELF presentation based on a survey responded by both native and non-native professionals in academia. Then authentic ELF presentations collected from under- and graduate-university students in Taiwan will be collected as the instruments. Fluent ELF users and native speakers of English will be invited to score these presentations based on the rubrics developed earlier. The scoring results of the two groups of evaluators will be compared and the discourse features of the better presentations will be analyzed. Finally, a set of instructional procedures together with classroom tasks will be designed and verified for real-classroom uses.
相關連結: http://grbsearch.stpi.narl.org.tw/GRB/result.jsp?id=2587687&plan_no=NSC101-2410-H006-084&plan_year=101&projkey=PE10107-0721&target=plan&highStr=*&check=0&pnchDesc=%E8%8B%B1%E8%AA%9E%E5%85%A8%E7%90%83%E5%8C%96%E5%B0%8D%E5%8F%B0%E7%81%A3%E8%8B%B1%E8%AA%9E%E6%95%99%E8%82%B2%E7%9A%84%E7%99%BC%E5%B1%95%E8%88%87%E6%8C%91%E6%88%B0-%E8%8B%B1%E8%AA%9E%E7%82%BA%E5%9C%8B%E9%9A%9B%E9%80%9A%E7%94%A8%E8%AA%9E%E5%B0%8D%E5%9F%B9%E9%A4%8A%E5%AD%B8%E7%94%9F%E8%8B%B1%E8%AA%9E%E8%A1%A8%E9%81%94%E8%83%BD%E5%8A%9B%E7%9A%84%E6%8C%91%E6%88%B0
